NORMALIZATION VIVA Q&A (1-LINE)
🔹 Basic Concepts
What is normalization? → Process of organizing data to reduce redundancy.
Why normalization is used? → To remove redundancy and avoid anomalies.
What is redundancy? → Repetition of data.
What is anomaly? → Problem during insert, update, delete operations.
Types of anomalies? → Insertion, update, deletion anomalies.

🔹 Functional Dependency
What is functional dependency? → Relationship between attributes.
Example of FD? → RollNo → Name.
What is determinant? → Attribute that determines another.
What is trivial dependency? → A → A (same attribute).
What is non-trivial dependency? → A → B (different attributes).

🔹 1NF (First Normal Form)
What is 1NF? → Table with atomic (single) values.
Main rule of 1NF? → No repeating groups or multivalued attributes.
Example issue in 1NF? → Multiple phone numbers in one column.
Solution for 1NF? → Split into multiple rows.
🔹 2NF (Second Normal Form)
What is 2NF? → 1NF + no partial dependency.
What is partial dependency? → Depends on part of composite key.
When does 2NF apply? → When table has composite key.
Solution for 2NF? → Split into separate tables.

🔹 3NF (Third Normal Form)
What is 3NF? → 2NF + no transitive dependency.
What is transitive dependency? → A → B and B → C.
Example of 3NF issue? → Dept → HOD.
Solution for 3NF? → Create separate table for dependent attributes.

🔹 BCNF
What is BCNF? → Every determinant must be a candidate key.
Is BCNF stronger than 3NF? → Yes.
Why BCNF used? → To remove remaining anomalies.

🔹 Keys & Dependency
What is candidate key? → Minimal unique attribute set.
What is primary key? → Selected candidate key.
What is composite key? → Key with multiple attributes.
What is super key? → Attribute set that uniquely identifies tuple.

🔹 Practical / Lab Based
What is unnormalized table? → Table with redundancy and repeating data.
First step in normalization? → Convert to 1NF.
How to identify partial dependency? → Check composite key.
How to identify transitive dependency? → Check indirect dependency.
Final goal of normalization? → Achieve 3NF or BCNF.

🔹 Important Differences
1NF vs 2NF? → 1NF removes repeating groups, 2NF removes partial dependency.
2NF vs 3NF? → 2NF removes partial, 3NF removes transitive dependency.
3NF vs BCNF? → BCNF is stricter than 3NF.

🔹 Exam-Oriented
Why normalization reduces redundancy? → By splitting tables logically.
Does normalization improve performance? → Sometimes reduces redundancy but may increase joins.
Is normalization always required? → Yes for good database design.











ADVANCED NORMALIZATION VIVA Q&A (1-LINE)

🔹 Conceptual Deep Questions
What is the main goal of normalization? → To eliminate redundancy and ensure data consistency.
What is denormalization? → Process of adding redundancy for performance.
When is denormalization used? → To improve query performance.
Is normalization always beneficial? → Not always, may increase joins.
What is data integrity? → Accuracy and consistency of data.

🔹 Functional Dependency (Advanced)
What is full functional dependency? → Depends on entire key.
Difference between full and partial dependency? → Full uses entire key, partial uses part.
What is transitive dependency example? → A → B and B → C.
What is closure of attributes? → Set of all attributes determined by a key.
Why functional dependency is important? → Helps in normalization process.

🔹 1NF Advanced
Can NULL values exist in 1NF? → Yes.
Can duplicate rows exist in 1NF? → Yes (unless key defined).
What is atomic value? → Indivisible value.
Does 1NF remove redundancy completely? → No.

🔹 2NF Advanced
Can 2NF exist without composite key? → Yes, automatically satisfied.
What happens if partial dependency exists? → Table is not in 2NF.
Does 2NF remove all redundancy? → No.

🔹 3NF Advanced
Does 3NF remove all anomalies? → Most but not all.
Can 3NF have redundancy? → Yes, in some cases.
Condition for 3NF? → No transitive dependency.
What is prime attribute? → Part of candidate key.
What is non-prime attribute? → Not part of candidate key.

🔹 BCNF Advanced
Condition for BCNF? → Every determinant must be candidate key.
Why BCNF is needed after 3NF? → To remove hidden anomalies.
Does BCNF eliminate all redundancy? → Mostly yes.

🔹 Anomalies (Important)
What is insertion anomaly? → Cannot insert data independently.
What is update anomaly? → Same data updated in multiple places.
What is deletion anomaly? → Deleting data removes useful info.
Example of update anomaly? → Changing HOD in multiple rows.

🔹 Decomposition
What is decomposition? → Splitting table into smaller tables.
What is lossless decomposition? → No data loss after split.
What is lossy decomposition? → Data loss occurs.
What is dependency preservation? → Dependencies maintained after split.
Why decomposition is needed? → To achieve higher normal forms.

🔹 Keys & Normalization
Role of primary key in normalization? → Identifies records uniquely.
Why composite key causes problems? → Leads to partial dependency.
Candidate key vs super key? → Candidate is minimal, super may have extra.

🔹 Practical Lab-Based
How to check 1NF in table? → Check atomic values.
How to check 2NF? → Check partial dependency.
How to check 3NF? → Check transitive dependency.
What is first step in solving normalization problem? → Identify keys.
What is final step? → Split tables accordingly.

🔹 Comparison Questions
1NF vs Unnormalized? → 1NF has atomic values.
2NF vs 1NF? → 2NF removes partial dependency.
3NF vs 2NF? → 3NF removes transitive dependency.
BCNF vs 3NF? → BCNF is stricter.

🔹 Tricky Questions (Exam Favorite)
Can a table be in 2NF but not in 3NF? → Yes.
Can a table be in 3NF but not in BCNF? → Yes.
Can a table be in 1NF but not in 2NF? → Yes.
Is normalization mandatory? → Yes for proper design.
